{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_methods",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Methods",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You've learned to store data in objects using attributes. Now let's add **methods** - functions that belong to a class and work with its data."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Methods let objects perform actions using their own data."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "what_are_methods",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Methods** are functions defined inside a class. They can access and use the object's attributes."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You've been using methods already: `list.append()`, `str.upper()`, `dict.keys()` are all methods!"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**The key difference:** Regular functions are independent, but methods belong to an object and can work with that object's data."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "creating_methods",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Creating Methods",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Define methods inside a class using `def`. The first parameter must be `self`, which refers to the object itself."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    def bark(self):\n        print(\"Woof!\")\n\ndog = Dog()\ndog.bark()",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Woof!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "We defined a `bark` method inside the `Dog` class. When we call `dog.bark()`, it prints \"Woof!\"."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`self` is required when defining the method, but you don't pass it when calling the method. Python handles `self` automatically!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "why_self",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Why do we need self?**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Methods need `self` to know which object they're working with. Without `self`, a method wouldn't know whose data to access."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Think of it like this: if you have 3 dogs, when one barks, the method needs to know which dog is barking!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
