        },
        {
            "id": "methods_with_parameters",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Methods with Parameters",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You might have already noticed that methods can take additional parameters besides `self`, just like regular functions."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Remember, `self` always comes first, then your other parameters. When calling the method, you only pass the other parameters - Python handles `self` automatically."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Player:\n    def set_score(self, points):\n        self.score = points\n    \n    def add_points(self, points):\n        self.score = self.score + points\n\nplayer = Player()\nplayer.set_score(50)\nplayer.add_points(30)\nprint(player.score)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "80"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`player.set_score(50)` sets the `score` attribute to `50` and `player.add_points(30)` adds `30` to the same `score` attribute resulting in a total of `80`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_parameters",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When defining a method with parameters, where does `self` go?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "After all other parameters",
                            "self is optional",
                            "Always first, before other parameters"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! self is always the first parameter.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "self must always be the first parameter in methods.",
                        "explanation": "Format: def method(self, param1, param2): ..."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "methods_calling_methods",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Methods Calling Methods",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Methods can call other methods of the same object using `self`:"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Calculator:\n    def set_value(self, num):\n        self.value = num\n    \n    def double(self):\n        return self.value * 2\n    \n    def show_double(self):\n        result = self.double()\n        print(f\"Double is: {result}\")\n\ncalc = Calculator()\ncalc.set_value(10)\ncalc.show_double()",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Double is: 20"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `show_double` method calls `self.double()` to get the doubled value. Using `self.` tells Python to call the `double` method of the same object."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This lets you break complex actions into smaller, reusable methods!"
                }
            ]
        },
